=='''Complex potential'''==
[[File:Jung50e.png|right|thumb| [[w:external ray|Uniformization]] of complement of Mandelbrot set]]
Complex potential is a complex number, so it has a real (real potential) and an imaginary part(external angle).
One can take its curl, divergence or its absolute value.
So on one image one can use more than one variable to color image.<ref>[http://www.quadibloc.com/math/mbint.htm | The Mandelbrot Function by John J. G. Savard]</ref>
===Real potential = CPM/M ===
In Fractint :
 potential =  log(modulus)/2^iterations

One can use real potential to:
*smooth (continuous) coloring<ref>[http://fanf.livejournal.com/110025.html Smooth colouring is the key to the Mandelbrot set by Tony Finch]</ref>
*discrete coloring ( level sets of potential)
*3D view

Here is Delphi function which gives level of potential : 


<source lang=pascal>
 Function GiveLevelOfPotential(potential:extended):integer;
  var r:extended;
  begin
     r:= log2(abs(potential));
     result:=ceil(r);
  end;
</source>

===External angle and external ( parameter) ray ===
First find angle of last iteration. It is easy to compute and shows some external rays as a borders of level sets.
** [[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/Mandelbrot_set#Binary_decomposition_of_LSM.2FM|binary decomposition of LSM/M]]  (see above)
** nth-decomposition : color of exterior is proportional to quadrant in which last iteration lands.  ( [[Fractals/Iterations_in_the_complex_plane/Mandelbrot_set#color_shows_in_which_quadrant_zn_lands|see below]] )

Then one go futher : 
* Wolf Jung explanation<ref>[http://www.mndynamics.com/indexp.html Wolf Jung explanation]</ref>
* Tomoki Kawahira paper <ref>[http://www.math.nagoya-u.ac.jp/~kawahira/programs/mandel-exray.pdf An algorithm to draw external rays of the Mandelbrot set by Tomoki Kawahira ]</ref>
* [http://patents.justia.com/patent/8484264 field line calculations], [http://420fractals.com/index.html images] and [http://www.youtube.com/user/MichaelTEverest videos] by Michael T Everest
==== Tests ====

'''The Wolf Jung test''' : 
The external parameter rays for angles  (in turns)
* 1/7 (period 3) 
* 321685687669320/2251799813685247 (period 51)
* 321685687669322/2251799813685247 ( period 51 )
Angles differ by about <math>10^{-15}</math>, but the landing points of the corresponding parameter rays are about 0.035 apart. <ref>[http://www.mndynamics.com/indexp.html Wolf Jung's test for precision of drawing parameter rays]</ref>

'''The test by G. Pastor and Miguel Romera''' 
The external parameter rays for angles  (in turns)
* 6871947673/34359738367 ( period 35 )
* 9162596898/34359738367 ( period 35 )
the central babies Mandelbrot sets of the cauliflowers located at -0.153756141 + 1.030383223i

(not that 34359738367 = 2^35 - 1)

